critical_issues: Discrepancies in Personal Particulars (PAN, Nominee Name) between transcript and MER.

Significant discrepancies in medical history: Customer initially denied having undergone tests (Q3) but MER states 'Yes' and customer later confirmed USG for kidney stone. MER states test results were 'No' (not normal) but customer stated 'reports are normal' for USG.
Discrepancy in Q16 regarding investigations: MER states 'No' but customer confirmed blood test and USG.
Discrepancy in Q18 regarding treatment/medication: Customer initially stated 'No' but MER states 'Yes' and customer is on hypertension medication.
Several sub-questions were missed by the agent (Q3.3, Q5.7, Q12.3, Q12.4, Q18.1-18.5).
Question 13 was incomplete as the agent moved on before the customer could answer.
recommendations: Agent must ensure all personal particulars are accurately verified against the application and MER.
Agent needs to ask all sub-questions as per the MER template to ensure a complete medical history is captured.
Agent should clarify inconsistencies in customer's responses, especially when an initial 'No' contradicts later information or MER data.
Agent should probe further when the customer states 'I don't remember' for critical information like medication names or specific medical details.

customer_satisfaction_indicators: Customer is cooperative and answers questions.
Customer provides detailed responses when prompted for medical history.
